<div dir="ltr"><font size="1"><span style="font-family:monospace,monospace"><font size="2"><font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif">Here&#39;s a transcript of when I checked out the install.  The sw1 switch was not up so I started it.  Both sx1 and sw1 have to be up in order to provide internet connectivity to the containers.  The sw1 and sx1 switches use iptables rules to route traffic to and from the actual internet connected interface.</font></font><br><br>kmw@Orabuntu-LXC:~$ sudo iptables -S | egrep &#39;sw1|sx1&#39;<br>-A FORWARD -i ens3 -o sw1 -j ACCEPT<br>-A FORWARD -i sw1 -o ens3 -j ACCEPT<br>-A FORWARD -i ens3 -o sx1 -j ACCEPT<br>-A FORWARD -i sx1 -o ens3 -j ACCEPT<br>kmw@Orabuntu-LXC:~$ <br><br><font size="2"><font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif">For the iptables rules to work, both sw1 and sx1 have to be up and have their ip addresses up.  So when I logged in I found that sw1 did not have an ip address for some reason, so I restarted it.  You can restart an OpenvSwitch either by using &quot;sudo service sw1 restart&quot;  or by sudo /etc/network/openvswitch/crt_ovs_sw1.sh and that same method applies for all the OpenvSwitches so you can substitute &quot;sx1, sw2,...&quot; etc for the sw1 in that command when starting or stopping a switch.<br><br>If you find there was some issue with a switch, it&#39;s usually best to get all the swtiches up and running in the correct state, and then restart all the containers. When restarting the containers, start the nameserver  container (in this case &quot;afns1&quot;) first, then &quot;sudo lxc-attach -n afns1&quot; and test that it has internet connectivity by doing &quot;nslookup <a href="http://yahoo.com">yahoo.com</a>&quot; and &quot;ping <a href="http://yahoo.com">yahoo.com</a>&quot; or some other website to make sure the nameserver container has internet connectivity.  If it does, then the other &quot;oraxx&quot; containers should too, so if that check is ok, you can bring up the ora66c10,11,12 containers.<br><br>BTW all of this should happen automatically on reboot with no restarts required or any of the above manual steps required.<br><br>Also, there should not be any need for any ctrl+c exits from the install.  If there is, which apparently you had to do, then it means that the box is too slow and some process was very bogged down during the install and &quot;seemed&quot; to hang but really it was running just very slowly, or it was running so slowly that subprocesses started hanging up, because the main point here is that this is a fully-automated install and there should not be any ctrl breaks needed during install.<br><br></font></font>orabuntu@pasadena1:~$ ssh <a href="mailto:kmw@172.6.129.30">kmw@172.6.129.30</a> -p 2222<br>The authenticity of host &#39;[172.6.129.30]:2222 ([172.6.129.30]:2222)&#39; can&#39;t be established.<br>ECDSA key fingerprint is SHA256:NALLHh8VEHQk+hz6htveXtCxL5TbbQshJuJrQx7NVYY.<br>Are you sure you want to continue connecting (yes/no)? yes<br>Warning: Permanently added &#39;[172.6.129.30]:2222&#39; (ECDSA) to the list of known hosts.<br><a href="mailto:kmw@172.6.129.30">kmw@172.6.129.30</a>&#39;s password: <br>Welcome to Ubuntu 16.04.4 LTS (GNU/Linux 4.4.0-119-generic x86_64)<br><br> * Documentation:  <a href="https://help.ubuntu.com">https://help.ubuntu.com</a><br> * Management:     <a href="https://landscape.canonical.com">https://landscape.canonical.com</a><br> * Support:        <a href="https://ubuntu.com/advantage">https://ubuntu.com/advantage</a><br><br>6 packages can be updated.<br>0 updates are security updates.<br><br><br>*** System restart required ***<br>Last login: Sun Apr 22 08:58:13 2018 from 64.137.219.113<br>kmw@Orabuntu-LXC:~$ sudo lxc-ls -f<br>[sudo] password for kmw: <br>NAME       STATE   AUTOSTART GROUPS IPV4                      IPV6 <br>afns1      RUNNING 0         -      10.209.53.2, 172.29.108.2 -    <br>afns1-base STOPPED 0         -      -                         -    <br>oel66c10   STOPPED 0         -      -    